withdraw these funds can inadvertently lead to a permanent loss of value. This is because if someone sends Ether to the contract, they may be unable to retrieve it. To avoid this, functions receiving Ether should be accompanied by additional methods that process or allow the withdrawal of these funds. If the intent is to use the received Ether, it should trigger a separate function; if not, it should revert the transaction (for instance, via \u003ccode\u003erequire(msg.sender == address(weth))\u003c/code\u003e). Access control checks can also prevent unintended Ether transfers, despite the slight gas cost they entail. If concerns over gas costs persist, at minimum, include a rescue function to recover unused Ether. Missteps in handling Ether in smart contracts can lead to irreversible financial losses, hence these precautions are crucial.\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003cp dir=\"auto\"\u003e\u003cem\u003eThere are 1 assembly blocks and merges them into a single one. However, when blocks contained \u003ccode\u003everbatim\u003c/code\u003e, their comparison was performed incorrectly, leading to the collapse of assembly blocks which are identical except for the contents of the \u003ccode\u003everbatim\u003c/code\u003e items. Since \u003ccode\u003everbatim\u003c/code\u003e is only available in Yul, compilation of Solidity sources is not affected. fact that \u003ccode\u003eblock.timestamp\u003c/code\u003e is only updated once per block and its value remains constant throughout the block's execution. If an operation happens at the exact second when \u003ccode\u003eblock.timestamp\u003c/code\u003e changes, it could result in unexpected behavior. To avoid this, it's safer to use strict inequality operators (\u003ccode\u003e\u0026gt;\u003c/code\u003e or \u003ccode\u003e\u0026lt;\u003c/code\u003e). For instance, if a condition should only be met after a certain time, use \u003ccode\u003eblock.timestamp \u0026gt; time\u003c/code\u003e rather than \u003ccode\u003eblock.timestamp \u0026gt;= time\u003c/code\u003e. This way, potential off-by-one errors due to the exact timing of block mining are mitigated, leading to safer, more predictable contract behavior.\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003cp benefits, enhancing code clarity and efficiency. Structs allow for the grouping of related data into a single entity, making the function's return values more organized and easier to manage. This approach significantly improves readability, as it encapsulates the data logically, helping developers quickly understand the returned information's structure. Additionally, it simplifies function interfaces, reducing the potential for errors when handling multiple return values. 0 2.83Z\"\u003e\u003c/path\u003e\u003c/svg\u003e\u003c/a\u003e\u003c/div\u003e\n\u003cp dir=\"auto\"\u003eFunction call arguments in Yul are evaluated right to left. This order matters when the argument expressions have side-effects, and changing it may change contract behavior. FullInliner is an optimizer step that can replace a function call with the body of that function. The transformation involves assigning argument expressions to temporary variables, which imposes an explicit evaluation order. FullInliner was written with the assumption that this order does not necessarily have to match usual argument evaluation order because the argument expressions have no side-effects. In most circumstances this assumption is true because the default optimization step sequence contains the ExpressionSplitter step. ExpressionSplitter ensures that the code is in \u003cem\u003eexpression-split form\u003c/em\u003e, which means that function calls cannot appear nested inside expressions, and all function call arguments have to be variables. The assumption is, however, not guaranteed to be true in general. Version 0.6.7 introduced a setting allowing users to specify an arbitrary optimization step sequence, making it possible for the FullInliner to actually encounter argument expressions with side-effects, which can result in behavior differences between optimized and unoptimized bytecode. Contracts compiled without optimization or with the default optimization sequence are not affected. To trigger the bug the user has to explicitly choose compiler settings that contain a sequence with FullInliner step not preceded by ExpressionSplitter. \u003ca href=\"https://blog.soliditylang.org/2023/07/19/full-inliner-non-expression-split-argument-evaluation-order-bug/\" rel=\"nofollow\"\u003eRef\u003c/a\u003e\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003cp <div class="markdown-heading" dir="auto"><h3 tabindex="-1" class="heading-element" dir="auto">[L‑2] increase/decrease or forceApprove allowance should be used instead of approve</h3><a id="user-content-l2-increasedecrease-or-forceapprove-allowance-should-be-used-instead-of-approve" class="anchor" aria-label="Permalink: [L‑2] increase/decrease or forceApprove allowance should be used instead of approve" href="#l2-increasedecrease-or-forceapprove-allowance-should-be-used-instead-of-approve"><svg class="octicon octicon-link" viewBox="0 0 16 16" version="1.1" width="16" height="16" aria-hidden="true"><path d="m7.775 3.275 1.25-1.25a3.5 3.5 0 1 1 4.95 4.95l-2.5 2.5a3.5 3.5 0 0 1-4.95 0 .751.751 0 0 1 .018-1.042.751.751 0 0 1 1.042-.018 1.998 1.998 0 0 0 2.83 0l2.5-2.5a2.002 2.002 0 0 0-2.83-2.83l-1.25 1.25a.751.751 0 0 1-1.042-.018.751.751 0 0 1-.018-1.042Zm-4.69 9.64a1.998 1.998 0 0 0 2.83 0l1.25-1.25a.751.751 0 0 1 1.042.018.751.751 0 0 1 .018 1.042l-1.25 1.25a3.5 3.5 0 1 1-4.95-4.95l2.5-2.5a3.5 3.5 0 0 1 4.95 0 .751.751 0 0 1-.018 1.042.751.751 0 0 1-1.042.018 1.998 1.998 0 0 0-2.83 0l-2.5 2.5a1.998 1.998 0 0 0 0 2.83Z"></path></svg></a></div>

<div class="markdown-heading" dir="auto"><h3 tabindex="-1" class="heading-element" dir="auto">[L‑3] Governance operations should be behind a timelock</h3><a id="user-content-l3-governance-operations-should-be-behind-a-timelock" class="anchor" aria-label="Permalink: [L‑3] Governance operations should be behind a timelock" href="#l3-governance-operations-should-be-behind-a-timelock"><svg class="octicon octicon-link" viewBox="0 0 16 16" version="1.1" width="16" height="16" aria-hidden="true"><path d="m7.775 3.275 1.25-1.25a3.5 3.5 0 1 1 4.95 4.95l-2.5 2.5a3.5 3.5 0 0 1-4.95 0 .751.751 0 0 1 .018-1.042.751.751 0 0 1 1.042-.018 1.998 1.998 0 0 0 2.83 0l2.5-2.5a2.002 2.002 0 0 0-2.83-2.83l-1.25 1.25a.751.751 0 0 1-1.042-.018.751.751 0 0 1-.018-1.042Zm-4.69 9.64a1.998 1.998 0 0 0 2.83 0l1.25-1.25a.751.751 0 0 1 1.042.018.751.751 0 0 1 .018 1.042l-1.25 1.25a3.5 3.5 0 1 1-4.95-4.95l2.5-2.5a3.5 3.5 0 0 1 4.95 0 .751.751 0 0 1-.018 1.042.751.751 0 0 1-1.042.018 1.998 1.998 0 0 0-2.83 0l-2.5 2.5a1.998 1.998 0 0 0 0 2.83Z"></path></svg></a></div>
<p dir="auto">All critical and governance operations should be protected by a timelock. For example from the point of view of a user, the changing of the owner of a contract is a high risk operation that may have outcomes ranging from an attacker gaining control over the protocol, to the function no longer functioning due to a typo in the destination address. To give users plenty of warning so that they can validate any ownership changes, changes of ownership should be behind a timelock.</p>

<div class="markdown-heading" dir="auto"><h3 tabindex="-1" class="heading-element" dir="auto">[L‑5] Solidity version 0.8.20 may not work on other chains due to <code>PUSH0</code></h3><a id="user-content-l5-solidity-version-0820-may-not-work-on-other-chains-due-to-push0" class="anchor" aria-label="Permalink: [L‑5] Solidity version 0.8.20 may not work on other chains due to PUSH0" href="#l5-solidity-version-0820-may-not-work-on-other-chains-due-to-push0"><svg class="octicon octicon-link" viewBox="0 0 16 16" version="1.1" width="16" height="16" aria-hidden="true"><path d="m7.775 3.275 1.25-1.25a3.5 3.5 0 1 1 4.95 4.95l-2.5 2.5a3.5 3.5 0 0 1-4.95 0 .751.751 0 0 1 .018-1.042.751.751 0 0 1 1.042-.018 1.998 1.998 0 0 0 2.83 0l2.5-2.5a2.002 2.002 0 0 0-2.83-2.83l-1.25 1.25a.751.751 0 0 1-1.042-.018.751.751 0 0 1-.018-1.042Zm-4.69 9.64a1.998 1.998 0 0 0 2.83 0l1.25-1.25a.751.751 0 0 1 1.042.018.751.751 0 0 1 .018 1.042l-1.25 1.25a3.5 3.5 0 1 1-4.95-4.95l2.5-2.5a3.5 3.5 0 0 1 4.95 0 .751.751 0 0 1-.018 1.042.751.751 0 0 1-1.042.018 1.998 1.998 0 0 0-2.83 0l-2.5 2.5a1.998 1.998 0 0 0 0 2.83Z"></path></svg></a></div>
<p dir="auto">The compiler for Solidity 0.8.20 switches the default target EVM version to <a href="https://blog.soliditylang.org/2023/05/10/solidity-0.8.20-release-announcement/#important-note" rel="nofollow">Shanghai</a>, which includes the new <code>PUSH0</code> op code. This op code may not yet be implemented on all L2s, so deployment on these chains will fail. To work around this issue, use an earlier <a href="https://docs.soliditylang.org/en/v0.8.20/using-the-compiler.html?ref=zaryabs.com#setting-the-evm-version-to-target" rel="nofollow">EVM</a> <a href="https://book.getfoundry.sh/reference/config/solidity-compiler#evm_version" rel="nofollow">version</a></p>

<div class="markdown-heading" dir="auto"><h3 tabindex="-1" class="heading-element" dir="auto">[L‑8] Consider implementing two-step procedure for updating protocol addresses</h3><a id="user-content-l8-consider-implementing-two-step-procedure-for-updating-protocol-addresses" class="anchor" aria-label="Permalink: [L‑8] Consider implementing two-step procedure for updating protocol addresses" href="#l8-consider-implementing-two-step-procedure-for-updating-protocol-addresses"><svg class="octicon octicon-link" viewBox="0 0 16 16" version="1.1" width="16" height="16" aria-hidden="true"><path d="m7.775 3.275 1.25-1.25a3.5 3.5 0 1 1 4.95 4.95l-2.5 2.5a3.5 3.5 0 0 1-4.95 0 .751.751 0 0 1 .018-1.042.751.751 0 0 1 1.042-.018 1.998 1.998 0 0 0 2.83 0l2.5-2.5a2.002 2.002 0 0 0-2.83-2.83l-1.25 1.25a.751.751 0 0 1-1.042-.018.751.751 0 0 1-.018-1.042Zm-4.69 9.64a1.998 1.998 0 0 0 2.83 0l1.25-1.25a.751.751 0 0 1 1.042.018.751.751 0 0 1 .018 1.042l-1.25 1.25a3.5 3.5 0 1 1-4.95-4.95l2.5-2.5a3.5 3.5 0 0 1 4.95 0 .751.751 0 0 1-.018 1.042.751.751 0 0 1-1.042.018 1.998 1.998 0 0 0-2.83 0l-2.5 2.5a1.998 1.998 0 0 0 0 2.83Z"></path></svg></a></div>
<p dir="auto">A copy-paste error or a typo may end up bricking protocol functionality, or sending tokens to an address with no known private key. Consider implementing a two-step procedure for updating protocol addresses, where the recipient is set as pending, and must 'accept' the assignment by making an affirmative call. A straight forward way of doing this would be to have the target contracts implement <a href="https://eips.ethereum.org/EIPS/eip-165" rel="nofollow">EIP-165</a>, and to have the 'set' functions ensure that the recipient is of the right interface type.</p>

<div class="markdown-heading" dir="auto"><h3 tabindex="-1" class="heading-element" dir="auto">[L‑13] Empty receive functions can cause gas issues</h3><a id="user-content-l13-empty-receive-functions-can-cause-gas-issues" class="anchor" aria-label="Permalink: [L‑13] Empty receive functions can cause gas issues" href="#l13-empty-receive-functions-can-cause-gas-issues"><svg class="octicon octicon-link" viewBox="0 0 16 16" version="1.1" width="16" height="16" aria-hidden="true"><path d="m7.775 3.275 1.25-1.25a3.5 3.5 0 1 1 4.95 4.95l-2.5 2.5a3.5 3.5 0 0 1-4.95 0 .751.751 0 0 1 .018-1.042.751.751 0 0 1 1.042-.018 1.998 1.998 0 0 0 2.83 0l2.5-2.5a2.002 2.002 0 0 0-2.83-2.83l-1.25 1.25a.751.751 0 0 1-1.042-.018.751.751 0 0 1-.018-1.042Zm-4.69 9.64a1.998 1.998 0 0 0 2.83 0l1.25-1.25a.751.751 0 0 1 1.042.018.751.751 0 0 1 .018 1.042l-1.25 1.25a3.5 3.5 0 1 1-4.95-4.95l2.5-2.5a3.5 3.5 0 0 1 4.95 0 .751.751 0 0 1-.018 1.042.751.751 0 0 1-1.042.018 1.998 1.998 0 0 0-2.83 0l-2.5 2.5a1.998 1.998 0 0 0 0 2.83Z"></path></svg></a></div>
<p dir="auto">In Solidity, functions that receive Ether without corresponding functionality to utilize or withdraw these funds can inadvertently lead to a permanent loss of value. This is because if someone sends Ether to the contract, they may be unable to retrieve it. To avoid this, functions receiving Ether should be accompanied by additional methods that process or allow the withdrawal of these funds. If the intent is to use the received Ether, it should trigger a separate function; if not, it should revert the transaction (for instance, via <code>require(msg.sender == address(weth))</code>). Access control checks can also prevent unintended Ether transfers, despite the slight gas cost they entail. If concerns over gas costs persist, at minimum, include a rescue function to recover unused Ether. Missteps in handling Ether in smart contracts can lead to irreversible financial losses, hence these precautions are crucial.</p>

<p dir="auto">It is recommended that Solidity contracts are fully annotated using NatSpec for all public interfaces (everything in the ABI). It is clearly stated in the Solidity official documentation. In complex projects such as Defi, the interpretation of all functions and their arguments and returns is important for code readability and auditability.<a href="https://docs.soliditylang.org/en/v0.8.15/natspec-format.html" rel="nofollow">source</a></p>

<p dir="auto">When developing smart contracts in Solidity, it's crucial to validate the inputs of your functions. This includes ensuring that the bytes parameters are not empty, especially when they represent crucial data such as addresses, identifiers, or raw data that the contract needs to process.
Missing empty bytes checks can lead to unexpected behaviour in your contract.For instance, certain operations might fail, produce incorrect results, or consume unnecessary gas when performed with empty bytes.Moreover, missing input validation can potentially expose your contract to malicious activity, including exploitation of unhandled edge cases.
To mitigate these issues, always validate that bytes parameters are not empty when the logic of your contract requires it.</p>

<div class="markdown-heading" dir="auto"><h3 tabindex="-1" class="heading-element" dir="auto">[NC‑8] Events are missing sender information</h3><a id="user-content-nc8-events-are-missing-sender-information" class="anchor" aria-label="Permalink: [NC‑8] Events are missing sender information" href="#nc8-events-are-missing-sender-information"><svg class="octicon octicon-link" viewBox="0 0 16 16" version="1.1" width="16" height="16" aria-hidden="true"><path d="m7.775 3.275 1.25-1.25a3.5 3.5 0 1 1 4.95 4.95l-2.5 2.5a3.5 3.5 0 0 1-4.95 0 .751.751 0 0 1 .018-1.042.751.751 0 0 1 1.042-.018 1.998 1.998 0 0 0 2.83 0l2.5-2.5a2.002 2.002 0 0 0-2.83-2.83l-1.25 1.25a.751.751 0 0 1-1.042-.018.751.751 0 0 1-.018-1.042Zm-4.69 9.64a1.998 1.998 0 0 0 2.83 0l1.25-1.25a.751.751 0 0 1 1.042.018.751.751 0 0 1 .018 1.042l-1.25 1.25a3.5 3.5 0 1 1-4.95-4.95l2.5-2.5a3.5 3.5 0 0 1 4.95 0 .751.751 0 0 1-.018 1.042.751.751 0 0 1-1.042.018 1.998 1.998 0 0 0-2.83 0l-2.5 2.5a1.998 1.998 0 0 0 0 2.83Z"></path></svg></a></div>
<p dir="auto">When an action is triggered based on a user's action, not being able to filter based on who triggered the action makes event processing a lot more cumbersome. Including the <code>msg.sender</code> the events of these types of action will make events much more useful to end users, especially when <code>msg.sender</code> is not <code>tx.origin</code>.</p>

<div class="markdown-heading" dir="auto"><h3 tabindex="-1" class="heading-element" dir="auto">[NC‑25] Empty <code>receive()</code>/<code>payable fallback()</code> function does not authorize requests</h3><a id="user-content-nc25-empty-receivepayable-fallback-function-does-not-authorize-requests" class="anchor" aria-label="Permalink: [NC‑25] Empty receive()/payable fallback() function does not authorize requests" href="#nc25-empty-receivepayable-fallback-function-does-not-authorize-requests"><svg class="octicon octicon-link" viewBox="0 0 16 16" version="1.1" width="16" height="16" aria-hidden="true"><path d="m7.775 3.275 1.25-1.25a3.5 3.5 0 1 1 4.95 4.95l-2.5 2.5a3.5 3.5 0 0 1-4.95 0 .751.751 0 0 1 .018-1.042.751.751 0 0 1 1.042-.018 1.998 1.998 0 0 0 2.83 0l2.5-2.5a2.002 2.002 0 0 0-2.83-2.83l-1.25 1.25a.751.751 0 0 1-1.042-.018.751.751 0 0 1-.018-1.042Zm-4.69 9.64a1.998 1.998 0 0 0 2.83 0l1.25-1.25a.751.751 0 0 1 1.042.018.751.751 0 0 1 .018 1.042l-1.25 1.25a3.5 3.5 0 1 1-4.95-4.95l2.5-2.5a3.5 3.5 0 0 1 4.95 0 .751.751 0 0 1-.018 1.042.751.751 0 0 1-1.042.018 1.998 1.998 0 0 0-2.83 0l-2.5 2.5a1.998 1.998 0 0 0 0 2.83Z"></path></svg></a></div>
<p dir="auto">If the intention is for the Ether to be used, the function should call another function, otherwise it should revert (e.g. <code>require(msg.sender == address(weth))</code>). Having no access control on the function means that someone may send Ether to the contract, and have no way to get anything back out, which is a loss of funds. If the concern is having to spend a small amount of gas to check the sender against an immutable address, the code should at least have a function to rescue unused Ether.</p>

<p dir="auto">While 100% code coverage does not guarantee that there are no bugs, it often will catch easy-to-find bugs, and will ensure that there are fewer regressions when the code invariably has to be modified. Furthermore, in order to get full coverage, code authors will often have to re-organize their code so that it is more modular, so that each component can be tested separately, which reduces interdependencies between modules and layers, and makes for code that is easier to reason about and audit.</p>

<p dir="auto">Critical functions in Solidity contracts should follow a two-step procedure to enhance security, minimize human error, and ensure proper access control. By dividing sensitive operations into distinct phases, such as initiation and confirmation, developers can introduce a safeguard against unintended actions or unauthorized access.</p>

<div class="markdown-heading" dir="auto"><h3 tabindex="-1" class="heading-element" dir="auto">[NC‑30] Event is missing <code>indexed</code> fields</h3><a id="user-content-nc30-event-is-missing-indexed-fields" class="anchor" aria-label="Permalink: [NC‑30] Event is missing indexed fields" href="#nc30-event-is-missing-indexed-fields"><svg class="octicon octicon-link" viewBox="0 0 16 16" version="1.1" width="16" height="16" aria-hidden="true"><path d="m7.775 3.275 1.25-1.25a3.5 3.5 0 1 1 4.95 4.95l-2.5 2.5a3.5 3.5 0 0 1-4.95 0 .751.751 0 0 1 .018-1.042.751.751 0 0 1 1.042-.018 1.998 1.998 0 0 0 2.83 0l2.5-2.5a2.002 2.002 0 0 0-2.83-2.83l-1.25 1.25a.751.751 0 0 1-1.042-.018.751.751 0 0 1-.018-1.042Zm-4.69 9.64a1.998 1.998 0 0 0 2.83 0l1.25-1.25a.751.751 0 0 1 1.042.018.751.751 0 0 1 .018 1.042l-1.25 1.25a3.5 3.5 0 1 1-4.95-4.95l2.5-2.5a3.5 3.5 0 0 1 4.95 0 .751.751 0 0 1-.018 1.042.751.751 0 0 1-1.042.018 1.998 1.998 0 0 0-2.83 0l-2.5 2.5a1.998 1.998 0 0 0 0 2.83Z"></path></svg></a></div>
<p dir="auto">Index event fields make the field more quickly accessible to off-chain tools that parse events. However, note that each index field costs extra gas during emission, so it's not necessarily best to index the maximum allowed per event (three fields). Each event should use three indexed fields if there are three or more fields, and gas usage is not particularly of concern for the events in question. If there are fewer than three fields, all of the fields should be indexed.</p>

<p dir="auto">The SMTChecker is a valuable tool for Solidity developers as it helps detect potential vulnerabilities and logical errors in the contract's code. By utilizing Satisfiability Modulo Theories (SMT) solvers, it can reason about the potential states a contract can be in, and therefore, identify conditions that could lead to undesirable behavior. This automatic formal verification can catch issues that might otherwise be missed in manual code reviews or standard testing, enhancing the overall contract's security and reliability.</p>

<p dir="auto">The functions below take in an unbounded array, and make function calls for entries in the array. While the function will revert if it eventually runs out of gas, it may be a nicer user experience to <code>require()</code> that the length of the array is below some reasonable maximum, so that the user doesn't have to use up a full transaction's gas only to see that the transaction reverts.</p>

<div class="markdown-heading" dir="auto"><h3 tabindex="-1" class="heading-element" dir="auto">[NC‑38] Contract should expose an <code>interface</code></h3><a id="user-content-nc38-contract-should-expose-an-interface" class="anchor" aria-label="Permalink: [NC‑38] Contract should expose an interface" href="#nc38-contract-should-expose-an-interface"><svg class="octicon octicon-link" viewBox="0 0 16 16" version="1.1" width="16" height="16" aria-hidden="true"><path d="m7.775 3.275 1.25-1.25a3.5 3.5 0 1 1 4.95 4.95l-2.5 2.5a3.5 3.5 0 0 1-4.95 0 .751.751 0 0 1 .018-1.042.751.751 0 0 1 1.042-.018 1.998 1.998 0 0 0 2.83 0l2.5-2.5a2.002 2.002 0 0 0-2.83-2.83l-1.25 1.25a.751.751 0 0 1-1.042-.018.751.751 0 0 1-.018-1.042Zm-4.69 9.64a1.998 1.998 0 0 0 2.83 0l1.25-1.25a.751.751 0 0 1 1.042.018.751.751 0 0 1 .018 1.042l-1.25 1.25a3.5 3.5 0 1 1-4.95-4.95l2.5-2.5a3.5 3.5 0 0 1 4.95 0 .751.751 0 0 1-.018 1.042.751.751 0 0 1-1.042.018 1.998 1.998 0 0 0-2.83 0l-2.5 2.5a1.998 1.998 0 0 0 0 2.83Z"></path></svg></a></div>

<div class="markdown-heading" dir="auto"><h3 tabindex="-1" class="heading-element" dir="auto">[NC‑49] Make use of Solidiy's <code>using</code> keyword</h3><a id="user-content-nc49-make-use-of-solidiys-using-keyword" class="anchor" aria-label="Permalink: [NC‑49] Make use of Solidiy's using keyword" href="#nc49-make-use-of-solidiys-using-keyword"><svg class="octicon octicon-link" viewBox="0 0 16 16" version="1.1" width="16" height="16" aria-hidden="true"><path d="m7.775 3.275 1.25-1.25a3.5 3.5 0 1 1 4.95 4.95l-2.5 2.5a3.5 3.5 0 0 1-4.95 0 .751.751 0 0 1 .018-1.042.751.751 0 0 1 1.042-.018 1.998 1.998 0 0 0 2.83 0l2.5-2.5a2.002 2.002 0 0 0-2.83-2.83l-1.25 1.25a.751.751 0 0 1-1.042-.018.751.751 0 0 1-.018-1.042Zm-4.69 9.64a1.998 1.998 0 0 0 2.83 0l1.25-1.25a.751.751 0 0 1 1.042.018.751.751 0 0 1 .018 1.042l-1.25 1.25a3.5 3.5 0 1 1-4.95-4.95l2.5-2.5a3.5 3.5 0 0 1 4.95 0 .751.751 0 0 1-.018 1.042.751.751 0 0 1-1.042.018 1.998 1.998 0 0 0-2.83 0l-2.5 2.5a1.998 1.998 0 0 0 0 2.83Z"></path></svg></a></div>
<p dir="auto">The directive <code>using A for B</code> can be used to attach functions (<code>A</code>) as operators to user-defined value types or as member functions to any type (<code>B</code>). The member functions receive the object they are called on as their first parameter (like the <code>self</code> variable in Python). The operator functions receive operands as parameters.  Doing so improves readability, makes debugging easier, and promotes modularity and reusability in the code.</p>

<div class="markdown-heading" dir="auto"><h3 tabindex="-1" class="heading-element" dir="auto">[NC‑50] [Solidity]: All <code>verbatim</code> blocks are considered identical by deduplicator and can incorrectly be unified</h3><a id="user-content-nc50-solidity-all-verbatim-blocks-are-considered-identical-by-deduplicator-and-can-incorrectly-be-unified" class="anchor" aria-label="Permalink: [NC‑50] [Solidity]: All verbatim blocks are considered identical by deduplicator and can incorrectly be unified" href="#nc50-solidity-all-verbatim-blocks-are-considered-identical-by-deduplicator-and-can-incorrectly-be-unified"><svg class="octicon octicon-link" viewBox="0 0 16 16" version="1.1" width="16" height="16" aria-hidden="true"><path d="m7.775 3.275 1.25-1.25a3.5 3.5 0 1 1 4.95 4.95l-2.5 2.5a3.5 3.5 0 0 1-4.95 0 .751.751 0 0 1 .018-1.042.751.751 0 0 1 1.042-.018 1.998 1.998 0 0 0 2.83 0l2.5-2.5a2.002 2.002 0 0 0-2.83-2.83l-1.25 1.25a.751.751 0 0 1-1.042-.018.751.751 0 0 1-.018-1.042Zm-4.69 9.64a1.998 1.998 0 0 0 2.83 0l1.25-1.25a.751.751 0 0 1 1.042.018.751.751 0 0 1 .018 1.042l-1.25 1.25a3.5 3.5 0 1 1-4.95-4.95l2.5-2.5a3.5 3.5 0 0 1 4.95 0 .751.751 0 0 1-.018 1.042.751.751 0 0 1-1.042.018 1.998 1.998 0 0 0-2.83 0l-2.5 2.5a1.998 1.998 0 0 0 0 2.83Z"></path></svg></a></div>
<p dir="auto">The block deduplicator is a step of the opcode-based optimizer which identifies equivalent assembly blocks and merges them into a single one. However, when blocks contained <code>verbatim</code>, their comparison was performed incorrectly, leading to the collapse of assembly blocks which are identical except for the contents of the <code>verbatim</code> items. Since <code>verbatim</code> is only available in Yul, compilation of Solidity sources is not affected. For more details check the following <a href="https://blog.soliditylang.org/2023/11/08/verbatim-invalid-deduplication-bug/" rel="nofollow">link</a></p>

<p dir="auto">Utilizing low-level calls like <code>.call{value: value}</code> for Ether transfers in Ethereum can be risky, as it can inadvertently allow malicious contract executions through fallback functions. To mitigate these risks and ensure safer Ether transfers, it is recommended to adopt more secure and explicit methods provided by reputable libraries such as OpenZeppelin. Functions like <code>Address.sendValue()</code> from OpenZeppelin provide a clearer and safer alternative for sending Ether, as they encapsulate necessary checks and error handling, ensuring that Ether is transferred securely and any errors are appropriately dealt with. This not only enhances the security of your smart contract but also improves code readability and maintainability, aligning with modern Solidity development practices.</p>

<div class="markdown-heading" dir="auto"><h3 tabindex="-1" class="heading-element" dir="auto">[NC‑55] Off-by-one timestamp error</h3><a id="user-content-nc55-off-by-one-timestamp-error" class="anchor" aria-label="Permalink: [NC‑55] Off-by-one timestamp error" href="#nc55-off-by-one-timestamp-error"><svg class="octicon octicon-link" viewBox="0 0 16 16" version="1.1" width="16" height="16" aria-hidden="true"><path d="m7.775 3.275 1.25-1.25a3.5 3.5 0 1 1 4.95 4.95l-2.5 2.5a3.5 3.5 0 0 1-4.95 0 .751.751 0 0 1 .018-1.042.751.751 0 0 1 1.042-.018 1.998 1.998 0 0 0 2.83 0l2.5-2.5a2.002 2.002 0 0 0-2.83-2.83l-1.25 1.25a.751.751 0 0 1-1.042-.018.751.751 0 0 1-.018-1.042Zm-4.69 9.64a1.998 1.998 0 0 0 2.83 0l1.25-1.25a.751.751 0 0 1 1.042.018.751.751 0 0 1 .018 1.042l-1.25 1.25a3.5 3.5 0 1 1-4.95-4.95l2.5-2.5a3.5 3.5 0 0 1 4.95 0 .751.751 0 0 1-.018 1.042.751.751 0 0 1-1.042.018 1.998 1.998 0 0 0-2.83 0l-2.5 2.5a1.998 1.998 0 0 0 0 2.83Z"></path></svg></a></div>
<p dir="auto">In Solidity, using <code>&gt;=</code> or <code>&lt;=</code> to compare against <code>block.timestamp</code> (alias <code>now</code>) may introduce off-by-one errors due to the fact that <code>block.timestamp</code> is only updated once per block and its value remains constant throughout the block's execution. If an operation happens at the exact second when <code>block.timestamp</code> changes, it could result in unexpected behavior. To avoid this, it's safer to use strict inequality operators (<code>&gt;</code> or <code>&lt;</code>). For instance, if a condition should only be met after a certain time, use <code>block.timestamp &gt; time</code> rather than <code>block.timestamp &gt;= time</code>. This way, potential off-by-one errors due to the exact timing of block mining are mitigated, leading to safer, more predictable contract behavior.</p>

<div class="markdown-heading" dir="auto"><h3 tabindex="-1" class="heading-element" dir="auto">[NC‑58] Returning a struct instead of returning many variables is better</h3><a id="user-content-nc58-returning-a-struct-instead-of-returning-many-variables-is-better" class="anchor" aria-label="Permalink: [NC‑58] Returning a struct instead of returning many variables is better" href="#nc58-returning-a-struct-instead-of-returning-many-variables-is-better"><svg class="octicon octicon-link" viewBox="0 0 16 16" version="1.1" width="16" height="16" aria-hidden="true"><path d="m7.775 3.275 1.25-1.25a3.5 3.5 0 1 1 4.95 4.95l-2.5 2.5a3.5 3.5 0 0 1-4.95 0 .751.751 0 0 1 .018-1.042.751.751 0 0 1 1.042-.018 1.998 1.998 0 0 0 2.83 0l2.5-2.5a2.002 2.002 0 0 0-2.83-2.83l-1.25 1.25a.751.751 0 0 1-1.042-.018.751.751 0 0 1-.018-1.042Zm-4.69 9.64a1.998 1.998 0 0 0 2.83 0l1.25-1.25a.751.751 0 0 1 1.042.018.751.751 0 0 1 .018 1.042l-1.25 1.25a3.5 3.5 0 1 1-4.95-4.95l2.5-2.5a3.5 3.5 0 0 1 4.95 0 .751.751 0 0 1-.018 1.042.751.751 0 0 1-1.042.018 1.998 1.998 0 0 0-2.83 0l-2.5 2.5a1.998 1.998 0 0 0 0 2.83Z"></path></svg></a></div>
<p dir="auto">Returning a struct from a Solidity function instead of multiple variables offers several benefits, enhancing code clarity and efficiency. Structs allow for the grouping of related data into a single entity, making the function's return values more organized and easier to manage. This approach significantly improves readability, as it encapsulates the data logically, helping developers quickly understand the returned information's structure. Additionally, it simplifies function interfaces, reducing the potential for errors when handling multiple return values. By using structs, you can also easily extend or modify the returned data without altering the function signature, facilitating smoother updates and maintenance of your smart contract code.</p>

<div class="markdown-heading" dir="auto"><h3 tabindex="-1" class="heading-element" dir="auto">[NC‑59] [Solidity]: Order of Argument Evaluation Disrupted in Non-Expression-Split Code by Optimizer Sequences with FullInliner</h3><a id="user-content-nc59-solidity-order-of-argument-evaluation-disrupted-in-non-expression-split-code-by-optimizer-sequences-with-fullinliner" class="anchor" aria-label="Permalink: [NC‑59] [Solidity]: Order of Argument Evaluation Disrupted in Non-Expression-Split Code by Optimizer Sequences with FullInliner" href="#nc59-solidity-order-of-argument-evaluation-disrupted-in-non-expression-split-code-by-optimizer-sequences-with-fullinliner"><svg class="octicon octicon-link" viewBox="0 0 16 16" version="1.1" width="16" height="16" aria-hidden="true"><path d="m7.775 3.275 1.25-1.25a3.5 3.5 0 1 1 4.95 4.95l-2.5 2.5a3.5 3.5 0 0 1-4.95 0 .751.751 0 0 1 .018-1.042.751.751 0 0 1 1.042-.018 1.998 1.998 0 0 0 2.83 0l2.5-2.5a2.002 2.002 0 0 0-2.83-2.83l-1.25 1.25a.751.751 0 0 1-1.042-.018.751.751 0 0 1-.018-1.042Zm-4.69 9.64a1.998 1.998 0 0 0 2.83 0l1.25-1.25a.751.751 0 0 1 1.042.018.751.751 0 0 1 .018 1.042l-1.25 1.25a3.5 3.5 0 1 1-4.95-4.95l2.5-2.5a3.5 3.5 0 0 1 4.95 0 .751.751 0 0 1-.018 1.042.751.751 0 0 1-1.042.018 1.998 1.998 0 0 0-2.83 0l-2.5 2.5a1.998 1.998 0 0 0 0 2.83Z"></path></svg></a></div>
<p dir="auto">Function call arguments in Yul are evaluated right to left. This order matters when the argument expressions have side-effects, and changing it may change contract behavior. FullInliner is an optimizer step that can replace a function call with the body of that function. The transformation involves assigning argument expressions to temporary variables, which imposes an explicit evaluation order. FullInliner was written with the assumption that this order does not necessarily have to match usual argument evaluation order because the argument expressions have no side-effects. In most circumstances this assumption is true because the default optimization step sequence contains the ExpressionSplitter step. ExpressionSplitter ensures that the code is in <em>expression-split form</em>, which means that function calls cannot appear nested inside expressions, and all function call arguments have to be variables. The assumption is, however, not guaranteed to be true in general. Version 0.6.7 introduced a setting allowing users to specify an arbitrary optimization step sequence, making it possible for the FullInliner to actually encounter argument expressions with side-effects, which can result in behavior differences between optimized and unoptimized bytecode. Contracts compiled without optimization or with the default optimization sequence are not affected. To trigger the bug the user has to explicitly choose compiler settings that contain a sequence with FullInliner step not preceded by ExpressionSplitter. <a href="https://blog.soliditylang.org/2023/07/19/full-inliner-non-expression-split-argument-evaluation-order-bug/" rel="nofollow">Ref</a></p>

<div class="markdown-heading" dir="auto"><h3 tabindex="-1" class="heading-element" dir="auto">[NC‑61] Consider using named function calls</h3><a id="user-content-nc61-consider-using-named-function-calls" class="anchor" aria-label="Permalink: [NC‑61] Consider using named function calls" href="#nc61-consider-using-named-function-calls"><svg class="octicon octicon-link" viewBox="0 0 16 16" version="1.1" width="16" height="16" aria-hidden="true"><path d="m7.775 3.275 1.25-1.25a3.5 3.5 0 1 1 4.95 4.95l-2.5 2.5a3.5 3.5 0 0 1-4.95 0 .751.751 0 0 1 .018-1.042.751.751 0 0 1 1.042-.018 1.998 1.998 0 0 0 2.83 0l2.5-2.5a2.002 2.002 0 0 0-2.83-2.83l-1.25 1.25a.751.751 0 0 1-1.042-.018.751.751 0 0 1-.018-1.042Zm-4.69 9.64a1.998 1.998 0 0 0 2.83 0l1.25-1.25a.751.751 0 0 1 1.042.018.751.751 0 0 1 .018 1.042l-1.25 1.25a3.5 3.5 0 1 1-4.95-4.95l2.5-2.5a3.5 3.5 0 0 1 4.95 0 .751.751 0 0 1-.018 1.042.751.751 0 0 1-1.042.018 1.998 1.998 0 0 0-2.83 0l-2.5 2.5a1.998 1.998 0 0 0 0 2.83Z"></path></svg></a></div>
<p dir="auto">Named function calls in Solidity greatly improve code readability by explicitly mapping arguments to their respective parameter names. This clarity becomes critical when dealing with functions that have numerous or complex parameters, reducing potential errors due to misordered arguments. Therefore, adopting named function calls contributes to more maintainable and less error-prone code.</p>
